I understand that Johnson (who is very clearly copying the Trump playbook in almost all respects - do they share some of the same supporters?) is hoping that his well thought out and measured critique of the Chequers Proposal, coupled with the brilliant plan that his Brexit chums have not yet been able to agree on (it must be a good plan because they have had 3 years or so to think about a Brexit Plan, so they can't be faulted for being hasty), will lead to a flood a new members signing up to become Conservative Party Members, As Boris did not realize that he did not like May's plan until mid-July his outraged supporters who were not already signed up Conservatives will not be eligible to vote in a leadership contest until at least mid-October, which will be after the Conservative Party Conference. The view seems to be that Boris's leadership bid will not now be until the Conference. The EU that dislikes Boris even more strongly than the UK general public does and most of his fellow Conservative MPs do, has been sowing confusion very successfully in the UK media who seem to have confused Barnier's remarks about the UK EU Withdrawal Agreement (aka The Brexit Agreement) being about the UK EU Future Trade Deal. Barniers has not suggested that the EU is likely to agree to the Chequers Proposal in the next 6 to 8 weeks if both sides are realistic, he was referring to the Withdrawal Agreement which according to the EU timetable was to have been agreed in October (2017 not 2018) and was agreed in principal on 8th Dec 2017. So if the Withdrawal Agreement has taken at least 3 times longer than planned, we should expect to see a trade deal agreement some time around autumn 2021. (Just as well it will be "the easiest Trade Deal in History" otherwise we might have a long wait!)

Parliament is in recess now until 4 September. For all (reasonable) intents and purposes, this means that May is safe from a Vote of No Confidence until Tuesday 4th of September. Assuming there is a successful VoNC against her on that day, she would have until Tuesday 18th September to regain the confidence of the House. If she cannot do that, an election would need to be called with a minimum 5 week ("25 working day") dissolution of Parliament beforehand.

After caving in to hard liner Brexiteers on Monday, Theresa May survived a vote in which 12 pro-EU tories voted for an amendment that she opposed that would have created a frictionless free trade agreement by January 2019 or the UK would have to be in the EU customs union. She won this vote by six votes, five of them coming from Labor and it lost by 307-301. She also backed off of her suggestion that they adjourn early for summer break because she would have lost that vote. If there is a vote of no confidence, she would have 14 days in which to win the vote of confidence, or a general election is held in two months. Unless something else blows up, it looks like she should survive until they go off for summer break next Tuesday and therefore likely to remain PM until October.

An early summer recess with MPs returning in September would leave a very small window of time for the government to collapse, or for May’s leadership to be successfully challenged. https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/jul/16/sending-mps-on-early-holiday-could-make-all-the-difference-for-may

Mrs May has made her Brexit plan (if it can be referred to as a plan) more difficult by appointing Javid to the Cabinet Brexit group as he does not support her ideas. I am not sure if he does not support the Mrs Mays's Customs idea because (like the EU and almost everyone else) he does not think it workable, or because he is now a hard Brexit supporter. In one sense it Mrs May's Customs options are irrelevant, because they have already been rejected as impractical (magic thinking) by the EU. While Mrs May insists that the border with Ireland will remain as it is, and that the UK will be doing free trade with 3rd countries once outside the EU, it appears to be impossible to see any way to achieve her objectives. There is now a three way split in the Conservative Party and any one of these groups could force Mrs May out. The Hard Brexit group insists on nothing that looks like a Customs Union (and Single Market) with the EU. It has no solution to the Irish Border (except possible scrap the Good Friday agreement which created the open border). The Soft Brexit group see the solution as staying in Customs Union and Single Market with the consequence of not having 3rd party free trade deals (but they could do deal to give services access to 3rd countries). The Rump group want some leadership and a practical solution found to Brexit. As the Brexit negotiations fail to produce any progress the Rump might decide a new leader is needed. I detect a hint that the Hard Brexit group are preparing their excuses for the failure of Brexit. Failure in their eyes would be to deliver a Brexit that did not have 3rd country trade deals, but if the choice is between the free trade deals (aka "getting a packet of crisps one day") and scrapping the open border and screwing up trade with Europe (aka "a three course dinner today") the Rump would prefer the "three course meal". The Hard Brexiteers are threatening to vote against a final Brexit Deal that does not given them what they promised (but that is impossible to deliver). This would allow them to claim that Parliament had betrayed Brexit and that if Mrs May had only done what they demanded the (impossible) Brexit they said people voted for would have happened. In other words they are trying to save their credibility for after Brexit when it fails to deliver. Getting rid of Mrs May would not help them, if one of the Hard Brexiteers were PM there still would be no way they could deliver Brexit as outlined by them. One of the many ironies of Brexit is that the Hard Brexiteers sold Brexit as "bringing back power to Parliament", to avoid giving Parliament any of power over a EU deal they claim that the referendum was very clear and all voters understood very clearly the issues such as the Irish Border, Customs Union, Single Market, 3rd Country Trade policies etc and as it was all so clear that Parliament does not need to say if the final deal is any good or not. If everyone knew exactly what they were voting for in June 2016, how is it that 23 months later the Cabinet can't agree what deal the UK wants with the EU? If it was so clear to the voters then, why is not known by the Cabinet today?

As far as I can make out the UK EU Withdrawal legal document (aka phase 1 of leaving the EU) will in all probability be "agreed" this week, but it will not be signed and ratified until much later. So even assuming the 25% or so of the text that is not yet agreed, can be agreed in the next few days, there is no certainty that it will ever have legal standing. In this case the "fall back position" regarding the Irish border is pretty meaningless. If, as happened with the Dec 2017 outline agreement on the Withdrawal, and Brexiteers cannot get an agreement to have an open border and at the same time have Northern Ireland outside the Single Market and Customs Union, then there seems nothing to stop the UK refusing to ratify the EU Withdrawal agreement at any future date and introduce a hard border. This is surely not what the EU intends, so I would assume that the EU would insist on some legal certainty that the Withdrawal Agreement stands. Unless this happens Mrs May would appear to be safe as PM until after 1 Oct because a "magic" solution to the Irish border and Unique Trade Deal will be theoretically be possible until proved impossible, which will not be until after 1st Oct. If the agreement has no legal standing then the "implementation" period is not certain either, so businesses are unlikely to be happy.

The next week is critical for Mrs May. If she refuses to agree the Brexit Phase 1 legal document drawn up by the EU then there will be no progress before the next EU meeting in June. So no certainty for a transition period after March 2019, business no-deal contingency plans will presumably start being implemented as businesses start to panic. If Mrs May crumbles and agrees the EU document then a hard Brexit is as good as dead, unless they get rid of Mrs May. So if Mrs May goes it could be in the next couple of weeks.
There's a lot of pressure on May but Corbyn isn't credible and there's no one in the Tory party who can wave a magic wand over Brexot.

The Hard Brexiteers seem to be adjusting their rhetoric. Rees Mogg for example now says he will accept the ECJ as long as the UK can (in theory) choose to ignore it. This is the legal situation of all countries outside the EU, including those like Norway who are in the EEA. They follow Single Market rules, use EU institutions, take note of the EFTA Court that follows ECJ rulings, but legally these countries can choose to ignore the EFTA Court (but of course if they do, they loose their trade deals with the EU). The fact that Rees Mogg is willing to go along with this seems to indicate that the Brexiteers know they cannot get the Hard Brexit they want thru parliament. If they can't get Hard Brexit thru parliament there is little point trying to kick May out. But another risk has emerged from MPs not happy about May's general non-Brexit performance. Its a cumulative problem of tough talk about action to deal with problems that results in nothing or next to nothing being done. e.g. action of plastic waste (bottles, coffee cups etc.) where action is promised that then doesn't; cheap rail travel that turns out to be rationed). The next test for Mrs May is what if anything she will do about (alleged) Russian terrorism in the UK and donations to political parties by Russians. May is now reaching the point were everything she does (or does not) is annoying lots of people, including Conservative MPs.

Tusk seems very clear that no progress will be made in Brexit talks until phase 1 (Withdrawl) is written into law. The big sticking point is the Irish border. There can be no solution to the border issue while Mrs May sticks to her red-lines of no Customs Union, no, Single Market (the ECJ can be got around by calling it the EFTA Court or something). It would seem unlikely that Tusk would want to proceed to Brexit talks Phase II until Phase 1 is complete, because with the UK red-lines in place its impossible to reach any agreement on trade that would not require a change to the NI/Ireland border. If there is no trade, deal a border will be needed, if there is bespoke deal a border will be needed, if there is Canada+++ deal a border will be needed.

Mrs May's position has been shown to be weaker than it appeared in December and early January. Having agreed a deal on Phase 1 of Leaving the EU it has become clear that Mrs May is not able to get the Brexiteers to accept it. The Implementation period asked for (by the UK) was agreed in principle as a period in which the UK would be outside the political institutions of the EU but that would otherwise maintain the status quo. Since then the Brexiteers have been insisting that during the implementation period the status quo would not apply to the way that new EU migrants would be dealt with, that the UK would expect to make (not just negotiate) trade deals with 3rd countries, not be subject to all EU rules and laws, and even that the UK might want to not have an implementation period. Since last week's Brexit Committee meeting the UK government has been unable to agree to provide any clarification as to what it wants. As it seems the Brexit Committee was deadlocked, but Mrs May felt unable to either present her view of the way forward (it is reported she did not offer any views at all) or to use to her position to break the deadlock it must be concluded that she is so weak that whatever view she expressed or supported would not have been supported by the Parliamentary Conservative Party (PCP). At some point the UK government must take decisions on Brexit. Mrs May seems to be hoping that some external event will miraculously unite the PCP to one view which she can then follow. So the question is will such an external event change things before the PCP gets tired of waiting of waiting for a miracle to happen? Or even if the miracle does happen will the PCP decide that Mrs May is no the person to implement whatever type of Brexit the miracle suggests can/needs to be delivered. Possible "events" are a Conservative rebellion by Soft or Hard Brexit MPs or by Conservative Peers, or the EU shuts down negotiations until the UK gets it act together, a very clear vote in the local elections due in May, or unions and employers demand action, Conservative donors publicly announce no more funding. The excuse that the PCP cannot agree on who would be better than Mrs May, is becoming rather thin as it looks like anyone would probably be better than nothing, and in reality having Mrs May as PM is not much different from having no one as PM. Mrs May seems to be running out of road down which to kick the can.

The broad history of Prime Ministerial changes in the UK in the post-war era have gone as follows: General Elections (1945; 1951; 1964; 1970; 1974; 1979; 1997; 2010) i.e. 53% of times Internal party challenges (1990; 2007) i.e. 13% of times Voluntary resignation owing to scandal, crisis or ill health (1955; 1957; 1963; 1976; 2015) i.e. 33% of times It should be said from the off that as there have only been 15 Prime Ministerial changes in 72 post-War years, the base rate of any change is c.21% with the split for three above categories (GE, internal challenge, voluntary resignation) coming in at c.11%, c.3% and c.7%

A bad day for T. May yesterday. All the media regardless of political views are agreeing that her cabinet reshuffle was badly done, from announcements made that were then withdrawn to ministers refusing to accept jobs. It had also been widely reported that elements that the media thought were good seem to be in spite of Mrs May, not because of her planning them. Pro and anti Brexit media is concerned that if she cannot organise the membership of her cabinet then negotiating a complex deal with the EU (and all member states) is a worry. The question is how bad May's performance has to get before the 1922 Committee decides that she has to go, in spite of their not being any other Conservative MP who looks likely to be able to rescue the government. The 1922 Committee will obviously be aware that another general election would probably make things worse for the Conservatives so they will want to avoid that at all costs. So if Mrs May goes it will not be due to another general election this year, but because the Conservative Party replaces her as leader. If that were to happen a new PM would have to complete the Brexit negotiations, which would require compromises to be made (May's "red lines" will not survive in negotiations) and so whatever Brexit was agreed (or not agreed) would not match any version that the electorate had voted on, which would surely increase demands for another General Election. Another General Election would be likely to reject who ever the May replacement was. The 1922 Committee will know this; the EU will know this, and both will act accordingly e.g. the EU will not offer a version of Brexit can the UK PM can present to the UK voters as a triumph because they will see a bad Brexit offer as forcing the UK to hold an election (to accept or Reject it). The 1922 Committee will see changing the PM has the first move in a process which is likely to lead to kicking the Conservatives out of power. So my conclusion is; bad as she is her many detractors in the Conservative Party will have to keep her as PM because if she goes its likely that the Conservative Party looses power.

The question is what could lead May to stop being PM. She could become ill or sick of the job (5% chance?). She could loose the support of the DUP and no longer command a majority in Parliament or she could be overthrown by hard line Brixiteers or hard line Remainers in the Conservative parliamentary party (15% to 25% chance). But a walkout by the DUP would not result in any conceivable majority government that would be more likely to support DUP views, so it is difficult to see any advantage to them in walking out. Replacing Mrs May with any Conservative that actually had any strong views of Brexit would cause more obvious fractures in the Conservative parliamentary party - a strong hard Brexit PM would not be supported by enough MPs to push a hard Brexit through parliament, a strong soft Brexit or no Brexit PM would not be supported by all Conservative MPs, but with support from most of the other parties in parliament they could command a majority for a soft Brexit or no Brexit. If DUP or Conservative rebels (of the hard or soft variety) meant May did not have a majority it would be bound to lead to calls for a general election, and the last general election did not go well for the Conservative Party or for the Hard Brexit cause so Conservatives will want to avoid another one.

If the Labour Party somehow manages to convince almost every other party to vote for their nominee and wins the race for a new leader, it will most likely be Jeremy Corbyn.

I can see May being knifed but the reality is she is weakened but no one else has the strength to quite push her out. And considering what a mess Brexit is turning into, I'm not sure anyone else is eager to be in the hot seat.

The polls suggest that Labour will perfom better. In the likely event of yet another early general election the polls might fluctuate a lot, however Theresa May isn't a good campaigner while Jeremy Corbyn might profit even more and get some decent gains. Unfortunately for the Tories there currently is no other candidate to replace her with and I highly doubt that there will be a suitable replacement in the near future.
Brexit is in enough turmoil as it is.
Pending the fallout of Brexit and the uncertainty in Germany, this doesn't appear to be likely. I can't imagine the Conservatives are anxious to hold snap elections given the last one in June 2017.
